Obesity and Education Background

We are interested in examining a relationship between obesity and educational level.

The education data set in the file education.csv summarizes education level in Wisconsin by zip code and sex with the percentage of men and women age 25 and older who have a bachelor’s degree or higher. There is one row per zip code and separate columns for females and males with a small amount of missing data.

The obesity data is broken down more finely: we have one row for each zip code, sex, and age range.

In order to join these data sets, we will want to reshape each so that there is one row per zip code and sex. The reshaped education data set will have columns zip, sex, and pct_bachelors with the percentage of individuals aged 25 and older of the given sex in that zip code with at least a bachelors degree. The reshaped obesity data set will have columns zip, sex and pct_obese with the estimated population percentage of adult individuals in the given sex and zip code that are obese (BMI > 30). We will only estimate these percentages in zip codes with no missing data among adults.

Note that our adult educational variable and adult obesity variables are calculated on different subsets of the adult populations within each zip code and sex (25+ for education, 18+ for obesity). This is okay as our comparisons are at the zip code level and not the individual person level.

The first few problems involve exploring and reshaping the individual data sets. Later problems ask you to do some data analysis with these reshaped and/or joined data sets.

Problems

1a. Write code to read in the education.csv file into a data frame named education_orig. You should have a data frame with 776 rows and three columns named zip, pct_m_bach, and pct_f_bach.

education_orig = read_csv("./../../data/education.csv")

1b. The next R chunk makes a summary calculation and prints it. Explain what each value represents.

education_orig %>% 
  drop_na() %>% 
  summarize(num = sum(pct_f_bach > pct_m_bach),
            n = n(),
            p_1 = mean(pct_f_bach > pct_m_bach),
            p_2 = mean(pct_f_bach == pct_m_bach))
## # A tibble: 1 × 4
##     num     n   p_1    p_2
##   <int> <int> <dbl>  <dbl>
## 1   596   773 0.771 0.0207

num is the count of zip codes where the percentage of women aged 25 and older with a bachelor’s degree or higher (pct_f_bach) is greater than the percentage of men aged 25 and older with a bachelor’s degree or higher (pct_m_bach).

n is the total number of zip codes in the dataset after removing any rows with missing data. In other words, it’s the sample size used for the calculations.

p_1 is the proportion of zip codes where the percentage of women with a bachelor’s degree or higher is greater than that of men. It’s calculated as num / n, providing the fraction of zip codes where women have a higher percentage of bachelor’s degrees than men.

p_2 is the proportion of zip codes where the percentage of women with a bachelor’s degree or higher is equal to the percentage of men with a bachelor’s degree or higher. It’s calculated by dividing the number of zip codes where pct_f_bach equals pct_m_bach by the total sample size n. Essentially, it tells us the fraction of zip codes where both genders have the same percentage of bachelor’s degrees.

2b. Describe what the pattern in the plot says about the relationship between female and male educational levels (as measured by the percentage of adults aged 25 and older with bachelor’s degrees) among the various zip codes in Wisconsin.

The plot reveals a clear pattern in the relationship between female and male educational levels across Wisconsin zip codes. The red line, representing equal percentages of bachelor’s degrees for both genders, serves as a reference. Notably, the majority of data points lie to the right of this line, indicating that in most zip codes, a higher percentage of females aged 25 and older have attained a bachelor’s degree or higher compared to males.

Additionally, the blue curve, which depicts the trend in the data, starts to the left of the red line before gradually moving to the right of the red line. This observation underscores that as the percentage of women with bachelor’s degrees increases, the corresponding percentage for men tends to increase as well. In other words, there is a positive association between the educational attainment of women and men in Wisconsin zip codes.

2c. What do you think might be true about the zip codes with strong outliers, for example, where percentages are 0% or 100%?

Zip codes with extreme outliers, where the percentages of either 0% or 100% are observed, may reflect specific local demographics or characteristics. For instance, zip codes with 0% could indicate areas where, for some reason, no women or men aged 25 and older have attained a bachelor’s degree or higher. Conversely, zip codes with 100% may suggest areas where all individuals in that age group have achieved a bachelor’s degree or higher, potentially due to the presence of a specialized educational institution or a small, highly educated population.

To provide a specific example, consider zip code 53706, situated on the UW-Madison campus. In this case, the 100% percentage for women could be attributed to the presence of a specialized educational institution. Most females in this zip code may either work on campus as professors or are pursuing postgraduate studies, creating a unique educational environment that results in this extreme value.

3a. Create a data frame named education in long format with a single row for each zip code and sex combination (so, two rows per zip code, one for females and one for males) using the pivot_longer() function. Prior to pivoting, drop rows with any missing data. Arrange the rows of the data set by zip code and sex. After the transformation, you should have the following columns:

  • zip = zip code; change its type to character

  • sex = sex; make the values "female" and "male"

  • pct_bachelors = % adults (aged 25+, of the given sex by zip) with at least a bachelors degree.

    3 (cont).

This data transformation will require reshaping data, changing data values, and transforming column names. There are (at least) two ways to think about doing this:

  • rename() the columns before reshaping.
  • recode() the values after reshaping.

Pick one and do it.

education = education_orig %>% 
     drop_na() %>%
     mutate(zip = as.character(zip)) %>%
     rename(male = pct_m_bach, female = pct_f_bach) %>%
     pivot_longer(cols = c(male, female),
                  names_to = "sex",
                  values_to = "pct_bachelors") %>%
     arrange(zip,sex)

obesity_orig = read_csv("./../../data/obesity.csv")
obesity_orig$zip = as.character(obesity_orig$zip)


obesity_new = obesity_orig %>%
  mutate(
    obese_pop = pop * (obese / n),
    non_obese_pop = pop * (1 - obese / n)
  )

adult_pop_sum = obesity_new %>%
  filter(age >= 18) %>%
  group_by(zip, sex) %>%
  summarise(total_pop = sum(pop))

ggplot(adult_pop_sum, aes(x = total_pop, y = sex)) +

  1. Use the newly joined education data set to estimate the percentage of women and men in the state with at least a bachelors degree. Report these percentages. (Note: You will want to determine the number of individuals for each zip code and sex with a bachelors degree before summing to get totals by sex for the whole state. You may ignore the detail that population totals are age 18+ and education level is for age 25+. You also should delete zip codes with missing education data prior to summing over zip codes for this calculation, but do not delete these rows from the education data set. Ensure that the zip variable is type character in both data sets before joining them. In addition, when using group_by() with multiple variables, all variables but the last are retained as grouping variables after summarize(). You may need to pipe a data set through ungroup() to eliminate residual grouping on occasion.)
combined %>%
  mutate(num_bachelors = pct_bachelors/100 * total_pop) %>%
  drop_na() %>%
  group_by(sex) %>%
  summarise(total_bachelors = sum(num_bachelors),
            pop_by_gender = sum(total_pop),
            percentage_bachelors = (total_bachelors/pop_by_gender) * 100)

adult_obesity_sum = obesity_new %>%
  filter(age != '05-17') %>%
  drop_na() %>%

  mutate(zip_count = n()) %>%
  filter(zip_count == 8) %>%

  summarise(total_obese = sum(obese_pop),
            total_pop = sum(pop))
